  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>OPEN LETTER TO GORDON, BRAD, AND ALAN</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p class=MsoNormal>Guys...<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I think you all have created a great game. I'm sure you have
also been well rewarded for your ingenuity and hard work. I don't know if the
size of those rewards have made you complacent like wealthy linebackers who
seem to avoid taking the risks that were taken by their predecessors, but
something has gone horribly a miss.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>A little context.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I am over thirty, married with kids, and work as an
executive in a professional services company. Now..that and 1.50 gets me a
plain cup of coffee at Starbucks. I include it only to explain that I am not
some Kewl Dood out to define his self worth by a virtual personna in a MMORPG.
This game one of the ways I choose to unwind, unplug, from the demands of work
and home. Writing this open letter is not part of unplugging or
unwinding...quite the opposite, but I have decided to invest this time. What I
ask is that you read and respond in this open forum. If that doesn't convince
you; my wife is really ticked that I spent all this time writing so a lack of
response will mean if got in trouble for nothing ;-)<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>My career and the success of my company is predicated on a
high degree of customer service. I'm sure many of the 300,000+ subscribers you
now serve have similar roles in the "real-world."<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Please, do not get defensive, but in my humble opinion, your
customer service is woeful. "How can that be? We have such a high
retention rate. Things must be pretty good."<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Can you do queries on your user logs to determine how many
of those accounts are still being used by original owners? Here is my
hypothesis. Few accounts are truly canceled. Many are either sold on Ebay or
absorbed into a guild. I know the guild with whom I play is supporting at least
1/2 dozen "canceled" accounts since they provide good utility in
terms of "porting", "resurrections,"
"mez-on-demand," etc.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Many people who play your game are, quite frankly, addicted.
I do not disparage them but this subset of your customer-base is largely
unaffected by poor customer service. They will argue and complain, but do
little else. However, when a suitable alternative to your product is available,
they will likely shift their addiction in that direction. What about Ashron's
call? Quite frankly, that game, from what I hear, doesn't hold a candle to what
EQ was (pre expansions) It just wasn't good enough to peel away your customer
base.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I think the major issues with the game came when you
expanded the characters beyond lvl 50 in an enviornment that was never designed
to support it. You have major balance issues between melee and casters because
of the wealth of melee items and the relative scarcity of both spells and
caster items.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I am starting to delv into the minutia and that is not my
intent so let me raise my points up a level.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I think you are doing a terrible job of communicating with
your customers. I am a customer and that is my perception. Many here seem to
have the same perception. Perceptions of one's customers is reality...trust me
it is. Your customers feel you are adversarial with them. They believe that you
think they will destroy "your" game with their unbalanced ideas.
Perhaps you are right...but they (we) are the customers so how do you
communicate your concerns while answering ours.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I'd like to offer a couple suggestions and then provide a
small case-study to illustrate why the implementation of such suggestions (or
ones similar) are needed.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I think Alan's idea for "Talk" threads was a good
one. That said, I do not believe Verant Management provided him the support or
infrastructure to make that good idea successful. This confuses me. If Verant's
data is accurate then you have approximately 300,000 active accounts which
equates to about $3 Million dollars in revenue monthly plus revenue from the
sale of retail boxes at $16 - $50 each. Surely, even after expenses and
R&D, there are enough funds to provide a robust and thoughtful customer
support engine.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I suggest that one member of your current staff be assigned
as advocate to each class. Such a person should have as their mission in life
to understand the wants and needs of that segment of customer.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each class should have an interactive page on the EQ website
through which to see a regularly updated status on their issues.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>You might say that you already have such advocates as part
of your tuning team. Great! Tell us who they are. Have them engage us. You
don't know how lucky you are to have a vibrant customer base that WANTS to tell
you what they think. Most companies have to pay 3rd parties to find
quasi-interested pseudo-customers who then provide their input...for a fee.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>These 14 folks would, of course, also have to maintain the
objectivity one would expect of a Verant employee as opposed to a purist
player. The "good-of-the-game" would temper the natural desire to
advance the position of their advocacy group beyond what is reasonable.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>The ideas put forth by the 14 would be managed similar to
how Alan has started the "talk" threads, but much more actively so.
Part of this open communication would include time lines and thoughts in
process. I know companies think of their project plans as some kind of top
secret document. "We can't share that with our customers; what if we miss
our projected timelines?"<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I would just love to see the look on one of my customer's
faces if I told them I would not share my team's project schedule. Communicate
with us; tell us what's up. If you miss a date...so what. It's a game to us,
not a mission critical enterprise application. Tell us why its going to be
delayed and give us a new date. You know, I bet dimes to donuts that if the
high-powered healing items were discussed in an open forum, even in general
terms so as not to ruin the excitement, the uncomfortable issues you now face
would have been avoided.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>So, to recap. <o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>1) Verant employed, class specific, advocates.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>2) Such advocates are either members of, or have significant
input to, the tuning team.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>3) All issues managed by advocates are communicated and
over-communicated to the interested community via class specific, verant
managed, web pages.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>4) Time lines for resolution to issues are published and any
slippage communicated in a timely manner.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Now....perhaps I am just full of hot air. Pehaps none of my
issues have any validity. Can I cite even one case example. Why yes...yes I
can.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Let us take the case of the Necromancer class. I play this
class and have since beta. I have a upper mid 50s character and am biased as
hell ;-)<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Here is some history which most of us know.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Everquest is a grouping game where experienced is gained by
vanquishing foes and such experience is shared among those participating. If
someone vanquished a foe by themself they got to keep all the experience.
Wow..that sounds like a great deal. <o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>And thus is born folks attraction to soloing characters. Of
the classes that could solo, Necromancers seemed to be able to do it best
although many would argue that Druids solo better. Even if that is the case,
Druids' solo ability is due to player ingenuity rather than Verant design.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Necromancers advanced quickly through low and middle levels
and jealousy developed among the other classes as they saw one class doing what
it would take a group of them to do. As is typical of human nature, they did
not explore the situation and realize such abilities were quite situational.
Open areas...good fear pathing...undead only...etc.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Such was the Necromancer class' abilities in this area that
pretty much everyone "hated them" They were tuned to place their
advancement in line with other classes.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>1) Pet damage was reduced<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>2) DoT damage was reduced in some situations<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>3) Pet damage was further reduced when dagger speed changes
were removed<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>4) Post 50 pets were made more powerful than the 49th lvl
pet by only the slighest of margins<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>5) Post 54 creatures universally resist lifetaps at which
point the entire class breaks down because its ability to restore health from
mana conversion is disconnected.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Well...that's a lot of change there. Perhaps too much, but
some things were added too. However, was the community ever asked if it wanted
to become a benevolent giver of mana? No. Communication. The hallmark of all my
points above was woefully lacking.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>The Necromancer community, of course, raised these issues.
Unfortunately most times in an immature and confrontational manner. The other
13 classes, still smarting from the Necromancer of yesteryear were quick to
raise the ante and call Necromancers overpowered and called for greater nerfs.
General ugliness ruled the day and continues to rule the day.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Fast forward to the recent past.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>The creation of Epic items. Great idea. Was any focus group
work done with the player base? What would they really want? What would truly
be epic. How would they balance that epic power with what was good for the
game. I'm betting this communication did not occur. The result, most classes
(>7) are unhappy with this ultimate reward. Some, Necromancers for example,
are outraged. Verant put a lot of time into these quests; I'm sure it wasn't
easy to code. Artists spent time creating textures and so on. My gosh, why
would you want to go to all that work only to have this "gift"
rejected with such venom. To be honest, the Necromancer epic item is both
embarrassing to look at and has an effect of marginal usefulness. This should
not be able to happen in a well run, customer-centric organization. To be
blunt, if 90% of your customer segment believes you made an error in your
product then you did. You made an error in the necromancer epic and should just
say so. Trust your customers to, in turn, reply, "Thanks for telling us
that, how can we help you fix the problem." TRUST YOUR CUSTOMERS!<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Dovetailing off the trust your customers comment, please
consider the following true scenario where my guild was going to Chardok to obtain
items for the Cleric epic mace.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Raid Leader: Please do not use Ignite/Chill bones; it
confuses the melee.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Necromancer: You realize it is my only DD<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Raid Leader: I know; I'm sorry ;-( Use your DoTs<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Necromancer: The critters die in less than 10 seconds; they
will do no good.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Raid Leader: Use your fast ones then<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Necromancer: Ummm...my fastest is 45 seconds<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Raid Leader: No way ;-(<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Raid Member: Why not have him make a pet<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Raid Leader: NO!!! Pathing is bad..pet will get us killed.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Necromancer: No DD, No DoT, No Pet. What should I do; I want
to help.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Raid Leader: This is going to suck, but give everyone DMF
and give your cleric/enchanter the balance of your mana. Sorry...<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Necromancer: Ok...<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Well that was how the raid went. What can Verant do about
that today. COMMUNICATE. State it. Tell us, "Ok...there are some problems
with your class. We are committed to fixing them. It will take some time. Susan
here is your primary contact at Verant and she will be working on your behalf.
We will get all your ideas down and then follow-up with some dates and next
steps. We will at least have the next steps posted for your feedback by date
XYZ.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Guys...this is basic business here. You will have amazed and
delighted customers. You will develop loyalty that will enable you to retain
customers through the release of "the next best thing."<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Brad...when was the last time you delighted a customer? Why
do people pay 2x as much to get a shirt at Nordstrom? Because Nordstrom strives
every day to delight every customer. OMG..my dog ate my shirt and I have a
meeting in Chicago; what am I going to do? As your checking into your hotel all
stressed out, the clerk hands you a package from Nordstrom with a shirt, your
size, in it,having been told of your dilemma and expressing the item to the
hotel at no additional charge. This is not B.S. this happened. If Macy's has a
sale on shirts tomorrow; will you see me there; hell no!<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Well, there you have it. Largely stream of consciousness
since I'm tired and irritated, which, Brad, is a far cry from delighted, I must
say.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Now is the time for the long pants. You three look at each
other and decide if you are going to continue the way you have been going, or
strive to delight your customers every day. Even when they are being major
pains in the ass. These customers are the ones that put food on your tables,
braces on your kids' teeth, and the Porches in your garages. Talk to us. Trust
Us. Listen to Us.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>For my part, I'd be glad to help in anyway I can. Shoot me
an e-mail; lets talk.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Best Regards,<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>A Customer<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

</div>

</body>

